    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2427897915" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2427897915" />
    <a title="Nathan Schrock" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63266255-nathan-schrock"><img alt="Nathan Schrock" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1630180424p2/63266255.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2427897915?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nathan Schrock" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nathan Schrock" href="/user/show/63266255-nathan-schrock">Nathan Schrock</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781441870476" href="/book/show/7825326-no-one-would-listen">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2427897915" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3895586254626203130">Apparently as a 12yo kid in 2008 I was oblivious to the news, so I didn&apos;t even know that the Madoff scheme occurred during my lifetime. Markopolos tells the story in a fascinating way, giving good layman&apos;s explanations of stock-exchange terms like &quot;front-running&quot; or &quot;split-strike conversion&quot;, but without getting bogged down trying to explain how the stock market works. As a dude with next to no knowledge of stocks, hedge funds, and capital markets, I understood Markopolos&apos; explanation of Madoff&apos;</span>
  <span id="freeText3895586254626203130" style="display:none">Apparently as a 12yo kid in 2008 I was oblivious to the news, so I didn't even know that the Madoff scheme occurred during my lifetime. Markopolos tells the story in a fascinating way, giving good layman's explanations of stock-exchange terms like "front-running" or "split-strike conversion", but without getting bogged down trying to explain how the stock market works. As a dude with next to no knowledge of stocks, hedge funds, and capital markets, I understood Markopolos' explanation of Madoff's scheme, so I'd say it was a win. 👍<br /><br />But the book really focused less on Madoff and more on Markopolos' struggle with the Security and Exchange Commission. Markopolos literally knew Madoff was a fraud years before he was caught, but the SEC wouldn't do anything about it. Of course, Markopolos only tells one side of the story, but it's a fairly well documented, condemning story for the SEC. Great book, and I recommend the narration by Scott Brick.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3895586254626203130" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


