<div id="review_2563828440" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2563828440" />
    <a title="Nancy Mills" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30276417-nancy-mills"><img alt="Nancy Mills" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1396666226p2/30276417.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2563828440?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nancy Mills" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nancy Mills" href="/user/show/30276417-nancy-mills">Nancy Mills</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2563828440" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18193772945981022816">&quot;Our Tax Dollars At Work.&quot; Harry Markopolos and his &quot;team&quot; of 3 other smart guys suspected that Bernie Madoff wasn&apos;t kosher more than a decade before he was finally found guilty of a Ponzi scheme that cost investors tens of billions and wiped out some fortunes and life&apos;s savings. Markopolos and his colleagues, independently and of their own initiative, did years of research and tried to blow the whistle on Madoff for years, but were blown off by everyone from the Wall Street Journal to the SEC. </span>
  <span id="freeText18193772945981022816" style="display:none">"Our Tax Dollars At Work." Harry Markopolos and his "team" of 3 other smart guys suspected that Bernie Madoff wasn't kosher more than a decade before he was finally found guilty of a Ponzi scheme that cost investors tens of billions and wiped out some fortunes and life's savings. Markopolos and his colleagues, independently and of their own initiative, did years of research and tried to blow the whistle on Madoff for years, but were blown off by everyone from the Wall Street Journal to the SEC. Shame, shame, shame on our own government for ignoring this issue. Had they listened when Markopolos presented his evidence in the first place, the public would have saved tens of BILLIONS of dollars and many lives would not have been destroyed.<br />"Financial thriller" sort of sounds like an oxymoron, but this is one. Markopolis writes in a conversational style; he is not F. Scott Fitzgerald nor does he try to be. (Can you imagine Faulkner writing about derivatives markets? I don't know what made me think of that...!). This author is a self-described "quant," what we might call a math nerd, who comprehends numbers in a way few people can, which is probably why the pencil pushers at the SEC didn't follow up on his constant badgering ... they couldn't wrap their little bureaucratic minds around what he was telling them.<br />Books reads like an account presented by a friend who is still mad and excited about what just happened to him. I found it delightful. Highly recommended!</span>
  <a data-text-id="18193772945981022816" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


